## Medium-Severity Findings

### 5. Eager Test — `OrderProcessor_FullWorkflow_Succeeds` (lines 57‑63)

Seven distinct production methods called (`ValidateOrder`, `CalculateTotal`, `ApplyDiscount`, `ReserveInventory`, `ProcessPayment`, `SendConfirmation`, `UpdateOrderHistory`). A failure in any one is hard to diagnose.

**Fix:** Split into one test per method, or if this is a deliberate integration/workflow test, rename to `[TestCategory("Integration")]` and document the intent.

### 6. Magic Number Test — `CalculateTotal_ReturnsCorrectAmount` (lines 84‑86)

`247.50`, `22.28`, `269.78` are unexplained. The reader cannot verify correctness without reading production code.

```csharp
// ✅ Fix — derive expected values from visible inputs or name constants
const decimal expectedSubtotal = 3 * 49.99m + 1 * 99.53m; // SKU-1 @49.99 × 3, SKU-2 @99.53
const decimal expectedTax = expectedSubtotal * 0.09m;      // 9% tax rate
Assert.AreEqual(expectedSubtotal, order.TotalAmount, "Subtotal mismatch");
```

### 7. Sensitive Equality — `GetOrderSummary_ReturnsFormattedString` (line 135)

`.ToString()` couples the test to the display format. Any cosmetic change (currency symbol, spacing) breaks it.

```csharp
// ❌ Current
Assert.AreEqual("Order ORD-001: 1 item(s), Total: $99.99", summary.ToString());

// ✅ Fix — assert on structured properties
Assert.AreEqual("ORD-001", summary.OrderId);
Assert.AreEqual(1, summary.ItemCount);
Assert.AreEqual(99.99m, summary.Total);
```

### 8. Exception Handling — `ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsValidationError` (lines 110‑118)

Manual `try/catch` instead of MSTest's built-in exception assertion. If `ProcessOrder` does *not* throw, execution falls to `Assert.Fail` — functional but fragile and noisy.

```csharp
// ✅ Fix — use Assert.ThrowsException (MSTest 4.x also offers Assert.ThrowsExactly)
var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ValidationException>(
    () => processor.ProcessOrder(order));
Assert.AreEqual("Order must contain at least one item", ex.Message);
```

